**Algebraic data types (sum types).**

Most developers live in a world of classes, interfaces, and primitives. They model "a thing that could be A or B or C" with inheritance hierarchies, string enums, nullable fields, or boolean flags. All of those leak - they let you represent *impossible* states.

Sum types flip that. Instead of "this object has fields that may or may not be populated depending on what kind it is," you say "this is *exactly one of* these variants, and each variant carries only the data relevant to it."

```typescript
// The boolean/nullable wasteland most codebases live in
type ApiResult = {
  success: boolean;
  data?: User;
  error?: string;
  retryable?: boolean; // only meaningful when success is false
}

// What you actually mean
type ApiResult =
  | { kind: "ok"; data: User }
  | { kind: "error"; error: string; retryable: boolean }
```

The second version makes illegal states unrepresentable. You literally *can't* have an error with data attached, or a success with a retry flag. The compiler enforces your domain logic.

Rust, OCaml, Haskell, and F# have had this forever. TypeScript gets close with discriminated unions. Even Python has `match` now. But most developers - especially in the Java/JS/C# mainstream - still reach for class hierarchies and `if (obj.type === "foo")` checks scattered across the codebase.

The reason it's underrated: it doesn't look impressive. It's not a framework, a pattern with a fancy name, or something you put on a CV. It's just... thinking more carefully about what values your program can actually hold. But it eliminates entire categories of bugs - not by catching them, but by making them structurally impossible to write.
